revision.text:
[[File:Union Station Washington, D.C. 1906.tif|thumb|Union Station in Washington, D.C. Designed by Daniel Burnham and completed in 1907, it is considered the epitome of Burnham Baroque.{{sfn|Harmon|Lewis|1993|page=65}}]]
'''Burnham Baroque''' is an [[architectural style]] developed by American architect [[Daniel Burnham]] at the end of the 19th and start of the 20th century. It relies heavily on a stripped [[Classicism]] with [[Baroque architecture|Baroque]] and [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]] inflections. It was popular primarily during the first three decades of the 20th century, particularly among designers of railroad stations.

==Genesis and character of the style==
The term was coined in 1956 by architectural historian Carroll L.V. Meeks{{sfn|Hines|1979|pages=395-396}} in his book ''The Railroad Station: An Architectural History''.{{sfn|Meeks|1956|page=129}}{{Efn|Wolf von Eckardt, architectural critic for ''[[The Washington Post]]'', has written that Burnham Baroque is the accepted term for this particular evocation of the mixed Neoclassical-Baroque-Beaux Arts style, and is as legitimate a descriptor as any other term.{{sfn|Babb|Anderson|Parks|1978|page=141}}}} Meeks credits Burham's staff architect, [[Charles B. Atwood]], with the genesis of the design. Consulting with railroad engineer J.F. Wallace, who ensured that the layout and tracks conformed to accepted industrial practice, Atwood designed the temporary railroad station which served the 1893 [[World's Columbian Exposition]] in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]. Atwood's use of the [[triumphal arch]] and [[colonnade]] in this structure was widely praised, and Meeks says Burnham strongly embraced the new style after the exposition.{{sfn|Meeks|1995|page=129}} Burnham Baroque became Daniel Burnham's favored architectural idiom.{{sfn|Harmon|Lewis|1993|page=64}}

Burnham Baroque relies heavily on Classicism,{{sfn|Hines|1979|page=288}} with restrained Baroque and Beaux-Arts styles{{Efn|Meeks points out that, at the time Burnham Baroque emerged, [[Art Nouveau]] and Beaux-Arts were often intermingled theoretically and in practice.{{sfn|Meeks|1995|page=131}}}} often incorporated into a building's fundamental structure (such as arches) as well as its details and ornament.{{sfn|Breslin|Van Dusen|2011|page=37}}{{sfn|Van Trump|1983|page=229}} [[Architectural historian]] [[Francis Morrone]] has gone further, arguing that Burnham Baroque combines the [[Chicago school (architecture)|Chicago school]] with the Neoclassic and Beaux-Arts elements used by the [[City Beautiful movement]]. But where the City Beautiful movement "slathers" ornamentation over a building, Burnham Baroque uses ornament to accentuate structure.{{sfn|Morrone|2003|page=119}}{{Efn|Morrone points out that Burnham Baroque shares many elements with the personal style of architect [[Louis Sullivan]].{{sfn|Morrone|2003|page=119}}}}

==Example structures==
[[File:1713 PACIFIC AVE. UNION DEPOT, TACOMA. REED AND STEM, ARCHITECTS. GENERAL VIEW FROM SOUTHWEST. - Union Depot Area Study, Tacoma, Pierce County, WA HABS WASH,27-TACO,6-10.tif|thumb|Union Station in Tacoma, Washington. Completed in 1910, this Burnham Baroque structure was designed by the firm of Reed & Stern.]]
Burnham Baroque was a highly influential architectural style.{{sfn|Meeks|1995|page=136}} Burnham Baroque was one of five architectural styles utilized by the architectural firm of [[Graham, Anderson, Probst & White]] in the 1920s.{{sfn|Chappell|1992|page=63}}{{Efn|This firm was the successor to Burnham's firm, D.H. Burnham & Company.{{sfn|Harmon|2011|page=265}}}} It was widely mimicked by architects designing large American metropolitan railroad stations.{{sfn|Meeks|1995|page=130}}

Examples of Burnham Baroque include:
*[[Birmingham Terminal Station]], [[Birmingham, Alabama]] (1909; [[P. Thornton Marye]], architect){{sfn|Meeks|1995|page=130}}
*[[Flatiron Building]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] (1910; Daniel Burnham and [[Frederick P. Dinkelberg]], architects){{sfn|Morrone|2003|page=118}}{{sfn|Nash|McGrath|2010|page=7}}
*[[Grand Central Terminal|Grand Central Station]], New York City, New York (1903; [[WASA Studio|Reed & Stern]] and [[Warren and Wetmore]], architects){{sfn|Meeks|1995|pages=129-130}}
*[[State Bank of Chicago|State Bank of Chicago Building]], [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]] (1928; Graham, Anderson, Probst & White, architects){{sfn|Chappell|1992|page=63}}
*[[Union Station (Pittsburgh)|Union Station]], [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]]  (1907; Daniel Burnham, architect){{sfn|Breslin|Van Dusen|2011|page=37}}
*[[Union Station (Tacoma, Washington)|Union Station]], [[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]] (1910; Reed & Stern, architects){{sfn|Meeks|1995|page=130}}
*[[Union Station (Worcester, Massachusetts)|Union Station]], [[Worcester, Massachusetts]] (1911; [[Watson & Huckel]], architects){{sfn|Meeks|1995|page=130}}
*[[The 925 Building|Union Trust Building]], [[Cleveland]], [[Ohio]] (1924; Graham, Anderson, Probst & White, architects){{sfn|Chappell|1992|pages=164-165}}
*[[Wabash Pittsburgh Terminal]], Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania (1904; [[Theodore Link]], architect){{sfn|Meeks|1995|page=130}}
*[[Washington Union Station]], [[Washington, D.C.]] (1907; Daniel Burnham, architect){{sfn|Hines|1979|page=285}}{{sfn|Harmon|2011|page=265}}

